In lmer() parameter REML by default is TRUE:

REML
logical scalar - Should the estimates be chosen to optimize the REML criterion (as opposed to the log-likelihood)?

Try maximum likelihood instead.

(md.random.ML<-lmer(bright~1+(1|operator),REML=F,data=pulp))

Estimates of variance of the random effect are different depending on the method.
Maximum likelihood method returns biased estimate, just like in simple case of estimating variance from the sample:

Ï2ML=1nâi=1n(xiâxÂ¯)2.ÏML2=1nâi=1n(xiâxÂ¯)2.

The REML method returns unbiased estimator for random effect variance.

For method ML we see AIC, BIC, log likelihood deviance and degrees of freedom for residuals.
But for REML these methods are not shown.
This is because likelihood ratio comparison is only valid for ML: the REML log likelihood function depends on predictors and the model can only be compared as long as predictors are the same.

For testing H0: Ï2Î±=0H0: ÏÎ±2=0 we cannot rely on assumption of normality of Ï2Î±ÏÎ±2.
This is the reason why lmer() does not return standard error for Ï2Î±ÏÎ±2 and why confidence interval Ï2Î±^Â±1.96StErrÏÎ±2^Â±1.96StErr is not accurate.

Test H0: Ï2Î±=0H0: ÏÎ±2=0 using anova().

md.null<-lm(bright~1,pulp)
anova(md.random.ML,md.null)
## Data: pulp
## Models:
## md.null: bright ~ 1
## md.random.ML: bright ~ 1 + (1 | operator)
##              Df    AIC    BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## md.null       2 23.080 25.072 -9.5400   19.080                         
## md.random.ML  3 22.512 25.499 -8.2558   16.512 2.5684      1      0.109
anova(md.random,md.null)
## refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)
## Data: pulp
## Models:
## md.null: bright ~ 1
## md.random: bright ~ 1 + (1 | operator)
##           Df    AIC    BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## md.null    2 23.080 25.072 -9.5400   19.080                         
## md.random  3 22.512 25.499 -8.2558   16.512 2.5684      1      0.109

  1. Comparison is done with the null model because we have only one predictor that can be used either in fixed or random effects model. These models are not comparable directly.

  2. Note that anova() returns identical results regardless of the method used.
    The reason is: anova() refits the model using ML in both cases.

  3. Comparison of the models is based on Chi-square statistic

    Ï2=â2LLik(md.null)+2LLik(md.random),Ï2=â2LLik(md.null)+2LLik(md.random),
    but the Chi-square assumption is not accurate in case of Ï2Î±=0ÏÎ±2=0.
    This leads to a bias in p-value: it is too conservative (higher).
    A rule of thumb is: divide the p-value by 2.
    When p-value suggests to reject H0H0 conservativeness of the estimate adds more confidence to the inference, i.e. if p-value is small then then we know that the real value is even smaller.
    But if p-value is not small enough to reject H0:Ï2Î±=0H0:ÏÎ±2=0 then we should be less confident concluding that Ï2Î±>0ÏÎ±2>0.

1.1 Prediction by random effect model

Calculate fixed effects.

grand<-mean(pulp$bright)
gr.a<-mean(subset(pulp,operator=="a")$bright)
gr.b<-mean(subset(pulp,operator=="b")$bright)
gr.c<-mean(subset(pulp,operator=="c")$bright)
gr.d<-mean(subset(pulp,operator=="d")$bright)
fixedEffects<-c(gr.a,gr.b,gr.c,gr.d)-grand
fixedEffects
## [1] -0.16 -0.34  0.22  0.28

Compare fixed effects with random effects to understand prediction by the random effects model.

fixedEffects/ranef(md.random)$operator
##   (Intercept)
## a    1.312118
## b    1.312118
## c    1.312118
## d    1.312118

The ratio shows the shrinkage factor.

Calculate the shrinkage factor using maximum likelihood estimates:

fixedEffects/ranef(md.random.ML)$operator
##   (Intercept)
## a    1.464481
## b    1.464481
## c    1.464481
## d    1.464481

ML method produces higher shrinkage.

Prediction by random effect model is done as follows:

  1. If brightness is predicted for new operator then prediction is the grand mean (fixed effect):
fixef(md.random)
## (Intercept) 
##        60.4
  1. If brightness is predicted for one of the operators selected earlier then the prediction is adjusted by estimated random effect:
fixef(md.random)+ranef(md.random)$operator
##   (Intercept)
## a    60.27806
## b    60.14088
## c    60.56767
## d    60.61340

Such predicting method is called Best Linear Unbiased Predictor (BLUP). Compare it with the otput of predict()

unique(predict(md.random))
## [1] 60.27806 60.14088 60.56767 60.61340

2 Blocks as Random Effects

Blocks usually represent effects that are not of direct interest, but cannot be avoided.

For example, response to a medicine may have slight differences for females and males. But the medicine is going to be prescribed regardless of gender anyway. So, grouping by gender represents blocks.

In the following example from page 161 4 processes of production of penicillin (4 treatments) are compared when blends of raw material, corn steep liquor, represent blocks.

mmod <- lmer(yield ~ treat + (1|blend), penicillin)

Test the significance of fixed effects using anova()

anova(mmod)
## Analysis of Variance Table
##       Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value
## treat  3     70  23.333  1.2389

The result is identical with ANOVA of lmod.
This is always the case when design is balanced, i.e. numbers of observations in groups are equal.

Also test the fixed treatments effects using maximum likelihood ratio test.
We need to use REML=F for that.

amod <- lmer(yield ~ treat + (1|blend), penicillin, REML=F)
nmod <- lmer(yield ~ 1 + (1|blend), penicillin, REML=F)
anova(amod,nmod)
## Data: penicillin
## Models:
## nmod: yield ~ 1 + (1 | blend)
## amod: yield ~ treat + (1 | blend)
##      Df    AIC    BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## nmod  3 127.33 130.31 -60.662   121.33                         
## amod  6 129.28 135.25 -58.639   117.28 4.0474      3     0.2564

Equivalence of models is not rejected.

We need to use ML method (REML=F) because under REML comparison of models with different fixed effects is not allowed: REML maximizing likelihood function without fixed effects which makes models with different fixed effects not comparable.

2.1 Longitudinal Data

In repeated measures designs same individual is studied multiple times.
If observations of the same individual are collected in time then the design is called longitudinal study or *panel study**.

Look at the example on page 184.

In this example consider results of Panel Study of Income Dynamics (PSID) that started in 1968.

data(psid)
head(psid)
##   age educ sex income year person
## 1  31   12   M   6000   68      1
## 2  31   12   M   5300   69      1
## 3  31   12   M   5200   70      1
## 4  31   12   M   6900   71      1
## 5  31   12   M   7500   72      1
## 6  31   12   M   8000   73      1

Plot the data

suppressWarnings(library(lattice))
xyplot(income ~ year | person, psid, type="l", subset=(person < 21),strip=FALSE)

The first 20 individuals are shown on the graph.
Some have slowly increasing income, typical for steady secure jobs.
Some are more irregular.

Group the data by sex.

xyplot(log(income+100) ~ year | sex, psid, type="l")

To remove the effect of very low salary briefly, add $100 to all incomes.
What can you tell by looking at the incomes by gender?

Fit a line to each subject of the first 20 group after centering the predictor at median level.

lmod <- lm(log(income) ~ I(year-78), subset=(person==1), psid)
coef(lmod)
##  (Intercept) I(year - 78) 
##    9.3999568    0.0842667

Now do the same for the whole sample.

slopes <- numeric(85);intercepts <- numeric(85)
for(i in 1:85){
lmod <- lm(log(income) ~ I(year-78), subset=(person==i), psid)
intercepts[i] <- coef(lmod)[1]
slopes[i] <- coef(lmod)[2]
}

Plot the results.

plot(intercepts,slopes,xlab="Intercept",ylab="Slope")

psex <- psid$sex[match(1:85,psid$person)]
boxplot(split(slopes,psex))

Compare the slopes using t-test.

t.test(slopes[psex=="M"],slopes[psex=="F"])
##

The results show that men have significantly higher incomes.
But women have significantly higher slope.

Can the income change be predicted by gender, age and education level?
Fit mixed effect model.

Use random slope and intercept per subject.

3 Mixed Effects in GLM Framework

Look at example on page 199.

The goal of the experiment is to show effects of surface and vision on balance.
The balance was observed for 2 different surfaces (foam or normal) and for different levels of vision: eyes open, eyes closed or dome placed over over head.
Balance is measured on a 2-point scale: stable or not.
Participants in the study: 20 females and 20 males ranging in age from 18 to 38 with measured heights (cm) and weights (kg).
Each participant is tested twice in each of the eye-surface combinations: total 12 measures per subject.

The ANOVA table shows strong subject effect.
But after adding the fixed effect subject parameters of gender, age, height and weight are not significant.
This is because each individual makes a dummy variable for which these factors are constant.

One way of fitting generalized model with mixed effects is glmmPQL() from MASS.
PQL stands for Penalized Quazi-Likelihood method.

Fit glmmPQL().

4 Sleep deprivation study

This example is described in Mixed-effects models project

Data sleepstudy from library lme4 come from the study by G. Belenky, et al (2003), Patterns of performance degradation and restoration during sleep restriction and subsequent recovery: a sleep dose-response study.

In the study a number of subjects from population of long-distance truck drivers were allowed only 3 hours of sleep each night during period of 10 days. Each day their reaction time was tested several times a day and averaged (measured in milliseconds).
In the data set there are measurements of 18 drivers from the study.

suppressWarnings(library(lattice))
head(sleepstudy)
##   Reaction Days Subject
## 1 249.5600    0     308
## 2 258.7047    1     308
## 3 250.8006    2     308
## 4 321.4398    3     308
## 5 356.8519    4     308
## 6 414.6901    5     308
xyplot(Reaction~Days|Subject,sleepstudy,type=c("p","r"))

It might be instructive to compare individual slopes and intercepts of subjects using linear models.
But there are reasons to consider random effects: subjects are selected randomly from a population and it may be important to draw conclusions about the whole population

As a result select a mixed model with intercept and slope as fixed effects and individual intercept and slope for each subject as random effects.

Fit 2 variations of the model:

  • One has conditional correlation between random effects of the same subject which allows to suggest in particular that individuals with initially higher reaction time are affected by sleep deprivation more.
  • The second model has independent random effects.

4.1 Model allowing correlation

Fit a model with fixed intercept and slope showing the general tendency and individual slopes and intercepts for each subject.

Fit model fm8 using lmer() with parameter REML=F including random effects for individual intercepts and slopes.

The model has 6 parameters:

  • Variance of subject intercept: its confidence interval is called .sig01 and shows significance
  • Variance of subject slope: confidence interval .sig03 shows significance
  • Correlation between random slope and intercept: confidence interval .sig02 shows insignificance
  • Residual variance: confidence interval .sigma
  • Fixed intercept effect, significant
  • Fixed slope effect, significant.

The fixed effect intercept shows that typical initial reaction time (0 days with restricted sleep time) is about 250 milliseconds.
Then on average each day of sleep deprivation increases reaction time by a little over 10 milliseconds. Residual subject-to-subject standard deviation is 25.592 shows that individual intercepts are expected to change within interval 250Â±50250Â±50 milliseconds or between 200 and 300 milliseconds.
For slopes we see that fixed slope is at 10.467 and random slope standard deviation is 5.7, so expected variation of slopes is 10.5Â±2â5.710.5Â±2â5.7 or between -0.9 and 21.9.

Check observed individual slopes and intercepts.

slopes<-numeric(18);intercepts<-numeric(18)
strtoi(names(table(sleepstudy$Subject)))
##  [1] 308 309 310 330 331 332 333 334 335 337 349 350 351 352 369 370 371
## [18] 372
for (i in 1:18) {
  lmod<-lm(Reaction~Days,subset=(sleepstudy$Subject==strtoi(names(table(sleepstudy$Subject)))[i]),
           sleepstudy)
  intercepts[i]<-coef(lmod)[1]
  slopes[i]=coef(lmod)[2]
}
summary(intercepts)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   203.5   229.4   258.1   251.4   273.0   290.1
summary(slopes)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  -2.881   6.195  10.430  10.470  13.550  21.760

The upper level of slopes variation is consistent with these calculations.
However the lower end of the range is lower than expected.

Correlation between individual slopes and intercepts is insignificant.
This means that there is no evidence of relationship between initial reaction time and the rate of change as a result of sleep deprivation.

Check copula to confirm no non-linear relationship between slopes and intercepts.

plot(rank(intercepts),rank(slopes))

4.2 Model with uncorrelated random effects

In order to request an independent random effects we need to specify individual intercept and individual slope as two terms.
However, formula Reaction~1+Days+(1|Subject)+(Days|Subject) is not going to work because (Days|Subject) is equivalent to (1+Days|Subject).
Set formula as Reaction~1+Days+(1|Subject)+(0+Days|Subject).
The last term in the formula can also be replaced with (-1+Days|Subject).

(fm9 <- lmer(Reaction~1+Days+(1|Subject)+(0+Days|Subject),sleepstudy,REML=F))

## .sigma       22.880555  28.787598
## (Intercept) 237.572148 265.238062
## Days          7.334067  13.600505

For this model there are still 2 random effects per subject, but this time there is no correlation between them.
Now all parameters are significant.

4.3 Comparison of the two models

The models fm8 and fm9 are nested and can be compared by anova().

anova(fm9,fm8)
## Data: sleepstudy
## Models:
## fm9: Reaction ~ 1 + Days + (1 | Subject) + (0 + Days | Subject)
## fm8: Reaction ~ 1 + Days + (1 + Days | Subject)
##     Df    AIC    BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## fm9  5 1762.0 1778.0 -876.00   1752.0                         
## fm8  6 1763.9 1783.1 -875.97   1751.9 0.0639      1     0.8004

The Chi-square statistic is small: 0.0639 relative to 1 degree of freedom, resulting in p-value of 0.8.
So, the hypothesis of equivalence between the two models is not rejected.

Alternative view of profile zeta plot is

xyplot(pr9,aspect=1.3,absVal=T)

Interpretation of zeta plots is similar to qq-plot.
In ideal case it looks close to straight line, indicating that confidence intervals are suitable.

The graph shows appropriate shape of zeta plot for Days, Intercept and sigma, but confidence intervals for .sigma1 and .sigma2 are skewed.

Profile pairs plot is created by:

splom(pr9)

It shows shape of bivariate log likelihood surface in the neighborhood of the solution.
Patterns below the diagonal are for z-scores, above the diagonal - original variables.

Pattern between .sigma1 and Intercept means that when fixed effect moves away from the estimate the corresponding random effects variance increases. Ideal case: circles, like for .sigma02-Intercept.

Check if adding random effect to the model makes enough difference.

Note. Comparison of models with and without random effects is not always reasonable.
Preference for a random effects in the model may not be a result of better fit, but interpretation of the model.

Package lme4 might have been updated and now can analyze objects of lm() and lmer(), but it appears that order in which models are given to anova() is important.

fm3<-lm(height~age+I(age^2),data=Oxboys)
anova(fm1,fm3)
## Data: Oxboys
## Models:
## fm3: height ~ age + I(age^2)
## fm1: height ~ age + I(age^2) + (1 | Subject)
##     Df     AIC    BIC  logLik deviance  Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)    
## fm3  4 1647.67 1661.5 -819.83  1639.67                             
## fm1  5  940.02  957.3 -465.01   930.02 709.65      1  < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

If direct comparison by anova() of objects lm() and lmer() is not working then there has been a known fix.

The reason for possible problem is that lmer() does not allow fitting a model with only fixed effects.

But fitting fixed effects model by lm() and mixed effects model by lmer() does not always allow comparison by anova().

The solution is: go to the predecessor of lme4 S3 library nlme and within that library use lme() for mixed effects instead of lmer() and use gls() for fixed effects instead of lm().

suppressWarnings(library(nlme))

Note slightly different syntax of calling mixed effects model by lme().

fm3<-lme(height ~ age+I(age^2), random= ~1|Subject,data=Oxboys)
fm4<-gls(height~age+I(age^2),data=Oxboys)
anova(fm3,fm4)
##     Model df       AIC       BIC    logLik   Test  L.Ratio p-value
## fm3     1  5  940.6658  957.8779 -465.3329                        
## fm4     2  4 1643.1330 1656.9027 -817.5665 1 vs 2 704.4672  <.0001

Likelihood ratio test shows that the two models are not equivalent.
Final choice of the model is fm1 including both quadratic term and random intercept.

5.3 Visualization of the fit

Visualize the fitted model.
See this description for more instructions on how to visualize panel data.

xyplot(height~age|Subject,data=Oxboys,fit=fm1,strip=FALSE,
       aspect=1.3,pch=16,grid=TRUE,
       panel=function(x, y, ...,fit,subscripts) {
         panel.xyplot(x, y, ...)
         ypred <- fitted(fit)[subscripts]
         panel.lines(x, ypred, col = "magenta")
        },
       xlab = "Standardized age", ylab = "Height (cm)")

Note that fitted(fit) extracts fitted values from fit=fm1, but these fitted values make one column including all subjects and will not be separated into panel specific parts.
Then subset corresponding to each panel is defined by argument subscripts that lattice passes to each panel. With subscripts each panel contains only fitted values corresponding to that subject.
